issue.title: Conflicting deployment error when updating AWS Lambdas with Provisioned Concurrency
issue.body:
Using Framework v1.60.3
Have an API deployed via serverless framework with valid ProvisionedConcurrency settings
Attempting to run an update results in AWS Cloudformation throwing the error:

> "A conflicting deployment is in progress"

This was the operation Cloudformation was trying to run:
`MethodXProvConcLambdaAlias`

No configuration changes were made in-between deployments.

Disabling provisionedConcurrency setting in configuration allows the API to be updated successfully

comment.body:
I am getting the same error with versionFunctions set to false. 

Also from 1.60.2 release notes:  Fix provisioned concurrency setup (closes #7059):
Fix provisioned concurrency configuration. Configure on alias, and not on version. Thanks to that it can work with versioning enabled.....

issue.title: AOT for bytecode and not binary/C
issue.body:
Hi,

Most of the AOT logic is generic and I think a JavaBootImage could be implemented which would output bytecode instead of machine code (through C), this would enable to benefit from most of GraalVM goodness on java applications without having to loose Java goodness (portability).
Indeed it would still loose the ~100ms of startup and wouldn't have the memory benefit but runtime performances would be increased potentially a lot eliminating dead code so it sounds worth doing it.

Hope it makes sense

comment.body:
Well, I am not a developer, but as I see it, please correct me @dougxc if I am wrong, there are some differences. First of the Graal JIT compiler and Graal native-image aka SubstrateVM, which is an JVM conform implementation in Java.

The Graal compiler is used to transform/ compiles bytecode via points-to analysis to native code. By doing so, there is a closed world assumption, in order to achieve following goals:

Motivation:
* fast startup, as in C fast startup
* instant peak performance
* small footprint as in pss (which brings us back to fast startup)   

Use-Case:
* function as a Service
* cli
* (embedded)

In order to compile everything ahead of time, all classes must be known during "generation"-time, in order ensure proper optimisation. Every bytecode instruction which is not resolved during points-to analysis will not written out to the heap later on. The classic classloading in the OpenJDK will load the bytecode/ verify and link it during runtime. This is quite expensive if you look at the Classloader implementation (synchronized all over). The bytecode in the classic OpenJDK is also placed in the Metaspace since Java8, even when most methods are not used in the loaded class. This will result in a bigger memory footprint and longer startup-times. Furthermore the AOT compiled code in SVM is already optimized in contrary to the classical JVM, which must run the code several times, first interpret it and later use C1 and C2 to compile to native code, which will result in CPU overhead due to profiling. At this point the bytecode takes up memory in the MetaSpace and in the Code-Cache for the OpenJDK. SVM can skip all this, because everything happend during generation time. Therefore SVM uses less memory and CPU resources, because no profiling must be done to reach "peak"-performance.

As I understand it, you suggest something like an hybrid. Get everything from both worlds. Dynamic classloading from unknown jars but the fast startup/ low memory footprint SVM. If you want something like this, you could just use a classic OpenJDK 13 with AppCDS on and some AOT (see JEP). 

If you were to enable dynamic classloading of jars, which are not known during generation time, you would need to include dynamic classloading (load, verify, link bytecode), a JIT, which profiles and compiles everything during runtime. To me it seems we are back to OpenJDK as is, but we could never achieve already mentioned goals.

Also see: http://www.christianwimmer.at/Publications/Wimmer19a/Wimmer19a.pdf
